t 1404","1380":"1380","ABT    1402":"about 1402","1404":"1404","about 1406":"about 1406","1402":"1402","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1375":"1375","ABT 1399":"about 1399","1397":"1397","1408":"1408","1406":"1406","Meifod, Montgomeryshire (Wales)":"Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,Meifod,Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Meifod, Montgomeryshire, Wales","Manafon, , Montgomery, Wales":"Manafon, Montgomeryshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tudur","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from the Old Celtic form <i>Teutorix</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘people, tribe’ and ‘ruler, king’. It has been described as a Welsh form of <i>Theodore</i>, but there is no connection between them, though it is ultimately akin to the Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  <b>Terry</b>   )."],"variants":[{"name":"Tudor","meanings":["The Anglicised form of the Welsh Tewdwr, a name derived from Theodore."]},{"name":"Tudyr","meanings":["Traditional: from the Old Celtic form <i>Teutorix</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘people, tribe’ and ‘ruler, king’. It has been described as a Welsh form of <i>Theodore</i>, but there is no connection between them, though it is ultimately akin to the Germanic name <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  <b>Terry</b>   )."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Tudur ap Dafydd was born in 1375. She married Tudur ap Llywelyn in 1395, in Manafon, Montgomeryshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 7 sons."},"et":{"1375–":"1375–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1397–Male":"1397–Surnud","1399–Male":"1399–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1402–Male":"1402–Surnud","1404–Male":"1404–Surnud","1406–Male":"1406–Surnud","1408–Male":"1408–Surnud","1375–Female":"1375–Surnud","ABT    1397":"umbes 1397","1395":"1395","ABT    1404":"umbes 1404","1380":"1380","ABT    1402"